Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into 1-inch-thick pieces. Remove and discard any large stems from @kale{4%ounce}; chop into bite-size pieces. Peel and mince @garlic{2%clove}.

Toss carrots on one side of a lightly oiled #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon} and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack for ~{10%minutes} (you'll add the meatloaves then).

While carrots cook, in a #medium bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup} with @water{1%tbsp}.

Add @ground beef{10%ounce}, garlic, @salt{1/2%tsp}, and pepper to bowl with panko mixture. Gently combine, then form into two 1-inch tall loaves.

Once carrots have roasted 10 minutes, remove #baking sheet{} from oven. Carefully place meatloaves on empty side of sheet. Lightly drizzle meatloaves with @olive oil{1%tsp}.

Roast until meatloaves are lightly browned and cooked through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add kale and a pinch of salt and pepper; cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly wilted, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @water{2%tbsp}; cook until kale is softened and water has evaporated, ~{2-3%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{} and set aside.

While kale cooks, in a second medium bowl, whisk together @cornstarch{1%tablespoon}, half the @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, and @water{1%cup} until smooth.

Heat pan used for kale over medium heat. Add cornstarch mixture and @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}. Cook, whisking occasionally, until cream cheese has melted and sauce has thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove from heat.

Carefully transfer half the cream sauce to a third medium bowl. Whisk in @beef stock concentrate{1}, @nutmeg{1/4%tsp}, and @sugar{1/4%tsp}. Taste and season with salt and pepper. Set aside.

Heat pan with remaining cream sauce over low heat. Stir in kale, remaining sour cream, and a pinch of sugar. Cook, stirring occasionally, until sour cream is incorporated and kale is tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove from heat; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide meatloaves, kale, and carrots between plates. Spoon gravy over meatloaves and serve.

> You've heard of Swedish meatballs... but Swedish meatloaves? That's right! These mini meatloaves are a larger, flatter version that's still warmly spiced (thank you, nutmeg) and smothered with that signature creamy gravy. Complete the comfort food trifecta with rich creamed kale and tender-sweet roasted carrots!